d to the open country preferred by other kookaburras) and does not live in cooperative breeding family groups, but singly, or when breeding, in pairs. Rufous-bellied kookaburras can be found in the middle story of the tropical rainforest, where they fly out directly and swiftly from their perch to seize large insects from trees. Despite their direct flight, rufous-bellied kookaburras are capable of very sharp twists and turns around the dense trees that form their habitat. They have been known also to hunt small vertebrates, but do so less frequently than the larger woodland kookaburras, and frequently are mobbed by smaller birds when they prey on their eggs or nestlings. Males are very aggressive in defending their territories, which average 2 to 2.5 ha (4.9 to 6.2 acres) in size, and sometimes fight intruders violently. Like their larger relatives, rufous-bellied kookaburras breed in termite mounds. Breeding usually takes place from May to October, though the young do not disperse fully until February, and pairs have not been known to attempt a second brood in one year. Two white eggs are laid, though the actual incubation period is not known. References", "shortSummary": "The rufous-bellied kookaburra (Dacelo gaudichaud), originally known as Gaudichaud's kookaburra after French botanist Charles Gaudichaud-Bea…", "habitats": ["热带雨林"], "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Rufous-bellied_Kookaburra_0A2A2796.jpg/960px-Rufous-bellied_Kookaburra_0A2A2796.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-dacelo", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-dacelo-gaudichaud", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-dacelo", "species": "taxonomy-species-dacelo-gaudichaud"}, "expandable": true, "x": -652.92, "y": -1322.75, "z": -164.33}, {"id": 